57th Road, west of 61st Street (right not shown), showing a rear view of homes facing on Maspeth Ave. The low 1½ story structure on the left is No. 6051 Maspeth Ave., and is at the S.W. corner. Here, G.M. Hyatt resided in 1852, opposite the Quaker Meeting House which was at the S.E. corner (extreme right and not shown) and at that date a schoolhouse, having been discontinued as a place of worship in 1810. St. Stanislos Roman Catholic Church was erected there. (In 1923.)

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

1922.

6032 Maspeth Ave., south side, east of 61st Street, showing what was probably the J. Moore house in 1873.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Maspeth Ave., south side, east of 61st Street, showing in the foreground the two homes of Mrs. Winterson in 1873. The one in the foreground was occupied by one Furman in 1873.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Maspeth Ave. (long view), west from 61st Street, showing in the foreground at the corner, the home of G.M. Hyatt 1852.  Extension was added by G. Hyatt in 1873.  The two homes beyond the first mentioned were owned by Mrs. Winterson in 1873.  Daves Reyes occupied this corner at about 1900.  P.S. 72 shows in the left center.

January 1924
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
